# ADR-0008 — Runtime Core Architecture

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

Pharos is being designed as a modular AI Operating System rather than a
single AI assistant.

The Runtime is responsible for executing user intent independently from
company-specific knowledge, AI providers, tools, memory systems, or product
logic.

As the Runtime evolved, multiple architectural components were introduced:

- RuntimeIntent
- RuntimeEngine
- RuntimePlanner
- RuntimePlan
- WorkflowBuilder
- Workflow
- WorkflowResult

Although each component had a well-defined responsibility, the overall
Runtime architecture was not yet documented as a single decision.

Without an explicit architecture, future work on:

- LLM planning
- Tool execution
- Memory
- Multi-agent systems
- Knowledge retrieval

could introduce unnecessary coupling and blur the responsibilities of each
layer.

This ADR establishes the Runtime Core as the stable foundation of the
Pharos AI Operating System.

---

# Decision

The Runtime shall be implemented as a deterministic execution pipeline where
each component owns exactly one responsibility.

The Runtime Core consists of seven layers:

```
RuntimeIntent
        │
        ▼
RuntimeEngine
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlanner
        │
        ▼
PlanningResult
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlan
        │
        ▼
WorkflowBuilder
        │
        ▼
Workflow
        │
        ▼
WorkflowResult
```

Each layer communicates only with its direct neighbour.

No component may bypass another layer.

---

# Responsibilities

## RuntimeIntent

Represents the execution request.

It is immutable.

It contains only the information required to describe the user's intent.

It contains no execution logic.

---

## RuntimeEngine

The public entry point of the Runtime.

Responsibilities:

- receive RuntimeIntent
- coordinate execution
- invoke RuntimePlanner
- invoke WorkflowBuilder
- execute the Workflow
- return WorkflowResult

The RuntimeEngine contains no planning logic.

The RuntimeEngine contains no workflow construction logic.

---

## RuntimePlanner

Transforms RuntimeIntent into RuntimePlan.

Responsibilities:

- planning
- decomposition
- analysis
- future AI planning

The planner never executes work.

Different planner implementations may exist:

- DefaultRuntimePlanner
- RuleBasedRuntimePlanner
- HybridRuntimePlanner
- LLMRuntimePlanner

---

## PlanningResult

Wraps the output produced by RuntimePlanner.

Currently contains:

- RuntimePlan

Future versions may include:

- diagnostics
- confidence
- planner metadata

---

## RuntimePlan

Represents the execution plan.

Current version contains:

- id
- title

Future versions may include:

- goals
- ordered steps
- constraints
- dependencies
- execution metadata

RuntimePlan is intentionally execution-independent.

---

## WorkflowBuilder

Transforms RuntimePlan into Workflow.

It is responsible only for workflow construction.

It performs no execution.

---

## Workflow

Represents executable work.

A Workflow encapsulates execution behaviour independently from planning.

Different Workflow implementations may exist depending on the execution
strategy.

---

## WorkflowResult

Represents the outcome of execution.

The Runtime always returns WorkflowResult.

Future versions may include:

- outputs
- artifacts
- execution statistics
- diagnostics

---

# Dependency Rules

RuntimeIntent has no Runtime dependencies.

RuntimeEngine depends only on contracts.

RuntimePlanner never depends on Workflow.

WorkflowBuilder never depends on Planner implementations.

Workflow never depends on Planner.

RuntimePlan never depends on Workflow.

Execution never depends on Company.

Company never depends on Runtime implementations.

Runtime remains completely independent from:

- HQ
- Products
- Employees
- Marketing
- Business logic

---

# Architectural Principles

The Runtime follows the following principles:

## Single Responsibility

Every Runtime component owns exactly one responsibility.

No class combines planning, workflow construction and execution.

---

## Dependency Inversion

The Runtime depends on contracts rather than implementations.

Concrete implementations are injected.

---

## Deterministic Bootstrap

The Runtime can execute without:

- AI
- LLM
- Memory
- Tool Registry
- Knowledge Base

The default implementation consists of:

```
DefaultRuntimeEngine

↓

DefaultRuntimePlanner

↓

DefaultWorkflowBuilder

↓

MinimalWorkflow
```

This deterministic bootstrap enables testing and provides a stable Runtime
foundation.

---

## Progressive Intelligence

Artificial Intelligence is an extension of Runtime,
not its foundation.

Future AI components replace contracts without changing the Runtime Core.

Examples:

```
DefaultRuntimePlanner

↓

LLMRuntimePlanner
```

```
MinimalWorkflow

↓

ToolWorkflow
```

```
LocalMemory

↓

DistributedMemory
```

The Runtime architecture remains unchanged.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Planner executes directly

Rejected.

Planning and execution are separate concerns.

---

## RuntimePlan executes itself

Rejected.

A plan is data.

Execution belongs to Workflow.

---

## WorkflowBuilder omitted

Rejected.

Separating planning from execution allows multiple execution models without
changing planners.

---

## Runtime coupled to AI providers

Rejected.

The Runtime must remain provider-agnostic.

LLMs are plugins, not architectural dependencies.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- highly testable
- deterministic bootstrap
- replaceable planners
- replaceable workflows
- clean separation of concerns
- provider independence
- suitable for multi-agent evolution

Negative:

- additional architectural layers
- slightly higher abstraction cost
- more interfaces than a minimal application

These costs are considered acceptable for an AI Operating System.

---

# Future Evolution

The Runtime Core defined in this ADR is considered stable.

Future development should extend—not redesign—the architecture.

Planned extensions include:

- Execution Strategies
- Tool Registry
- RuntimePlan enrichment
- LLM planners
- Memory providers
- Knowledge providers
- Agent Runtime
- Multi-agent orchestration

None of these extensions should require changes to the Runtime Core
architecture defined by this ADR.

